        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Laredo, TX: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Laredo, TX, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Laredo Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the International Fire Code (IFC) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Laredo Fire Extinguisher Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Laredo enforces the International Fire Code (IFC), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Laredo's status as the busiest inland port in the United States creates a commercial landscape dominated by warehouse and distribution facilities, freight logistics operations, manufacturing near the World Trade Bridge, and a significant retail and hospitality sector serving the border trade economy. Laredo's intense summer heat — regularly exceeding 105°F — accelerates dry chemical agent degradation and increases the risk of pressure gauge failures in extinguishers stored in unventilated spaces.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, and the tamper seal and pull pin are intact. Document every check. Absence of monthly records significantly increases liability exposure in the event of an incident or enforcement action.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle, and attaches a dated service tag. Texas requires fire extinguisher service to be performed by a technician licensed through the Texas Department of Insurance (TDI) State Fire Marshal's Office under a Portable Fire Extinguisher license. Verify licensing at tdi.texas.gov/fire before scheduling service. Any failed unit must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation. This typically includes a full recharge after examination. Missing the 6-year exam is frequently cited during Laredo Fire Department commercial property inspections.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must pass hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned and cannot be returned to service. Budget for some units to require replacement at this interval.</p>
